abstract: Are the wealthy a liability in 2020? Or will they help get him elected?
snippet: Are the wealthy a liability in 2020? Or will they help get him elected?
lead_paragraph: At an annual charity fund-raiser in October, Anna Wintour, the editor of Vogue, shared a table with the designer Michael Kors and Pete Buttigieg, then the mayor of South Bend, Ind., who wore one of his trademark navy suits.

abstract: The quickest way to get a President Stacey Abrams or President Pete Buttigieg is to first elect a President Biden.

lead_paragraph: You may have heard an old crank in a big house ranting about appliances and unflushable toilets the other day. “Remember the dishwasher, you’d press it, boom — there’d be like an explosion,” he said, apropos of nothing. “Now you press it 12 times.”

abstract: Corrections that appeared in print on Friday, Jan. 3, 2020.
snippet: Corrections that appeared in print on Friday, Jan. 3, 2020.
lead_paragraph: An article on Tuesday about Carlos Ghosn’s escape from Japan misstated the total amount Carlos Ghosn paid in bail. It was 1.5 billion yen, or about $13.8 million, not $9 million. The error was repeated in two other articles on Wednesday.

abstract: A day after a deceptively edited video of him spread on social media, Joseph R. Biden Jr. cautioned that the Democratic nominee would be vulnerable to false information in the general election.
snippet: A day after a deceptively edited video of him spread on social media, Joseph R. Biden Jr. cautioned that the Democratic nominee would be vulnerable to false information in the general election.
lead_paragraph: ANAMOSA, Iowa — As the Democratic presidential candidates fanned out across Iowa and New Hampshire on Thursday to address voters still scarred by President Trump’s victory in the 2016 election, Joseph R. Biden Jr. argued that any Democratic nominee would be vulnerable to baseless criticism and disinformation in the general election.

abstract: The remaining candidates should emulate his fighting words — and try to win him to their side.
snippet: The remaining candidates should emulate his fighting words — and try to win him to their side.
lead_paragraph: Julián Castro is the latest Democrat to drop out of the 2020 presidential race. He will probably receive more press coverage today and tomorrow than he has on any other day since he announced his candidacy. But unlike other Democrats who have thrown in the towel, Mr. Castro should continue to have a significant impact on the presidential campaign.

headline_main: Julián Castro Is Worth More Out of the Presidential Race Than He Was in It
headline_print_headline: Julián Castro Is Worth More Out of the Race Than In

abstract: Fund-raising numbers for the fourth quarter of 2019 show an unusually high number of viable campaigns. Waiting for the winner: President Trump and his huge war chest.
snippet: Fund-raising numbers for the fourth quarter of 2019 show an unusually high number of viable campaigns. Waiting for the winner: President Trump and his huge war chest.
lead_paragraph: A flood of money rushed into the presidential race in the last three months of 2019, producing an unusually large number of Democratic candidates with the resources to battle deep into the 2020 primary calendar, all vying for the right to face an incumbent president boasting his own enormous war chest.

abstract: Mr. Biden’s total, while far short of the haul that Senator Bernie Sanders announced earlier Thursday, was an improvement from the previous quarter.
snippet: Mr. Biden’s total, while far short of the haul that Senator Bernie Sanders announced earlier Thursday, was an improvement from the previous quarter.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Joseph R. Biden Jr. said on Thursday that he had raised $22.7 million in the fourth quarter of 2019, a significant improvement from his lackluster fund-raising performance in the previous three months.

headline_main: Joe Biden Says He Raised $22.7 Million in the Fourth Quarter

abstract: Mr. Sanders’s total is the largest three-month haul disclosed by any candidate so far in the Democratic primary race.
snippet: Mr. Sanders’s total is the largest three-month haul disclosed by any candidate so far in the Democratic primary race.
lead_paragraph: DES MOINES — Senator Bernie Sanders of Vermont raised more than $34.5 million in the fourth quarter of 2019, his presidential campaign said Thursday, yet another display of his enduring financial might fueled by a huge base of grass-roots donors.
